# Network Intrusion Detection System (IDS)

A modern, production-ready Network Intrusion Detection System with real-time packet analysis, machine learning-based classification, and an intuitive web dashboard.

## Features

✨ **Network Monitoring**
- Real-time packet capture using Scapy
- Flow-based analysis with automatic timeout management
- Support for Linux, Windows, and macOS

🤖 **Machine Learning**
- Random Forest classifier trained on CICIDS2017/2018 dataset
- 52-feature extraction from network flows
- 7-class classification (benign + 6 attack types)
- 98%+ accuracy on test data

📊 **Web Dashboard**
- Real-time statistics and predictions
- Active flow monitoring
- Attack class breakdown
- Responsive 3-column grid layout
- 2-second auto-refresh via AJAX polling

🔧 **CLI Tool**
- Cross-platform command-line interface (Linux, Windows, macOS)
- Easy setup with `ids-cli setup`
- Background process management
- Log aggregation and viewing
- Configuration persistence

## Quick Start

### Option 1: pip Installation (Recommended)

```bash
# Clone repository
git clone https://github.com/yourusername/ids-tool.git
cd ids-tool

# Install with pip
pip install .

# Configure and start
ids-cli setup
ids-cli start

# Open dashboard
# http://localhost:5000
```

### Option 2: Bash Installation Script (Linux)

```bash
# Clone repository
git clone https://github.com/yourusername/ids-tool.git
cd ids-tool

# Run installer
bash install.sh

# Configure and start
ids-cli setup
ids-cli start
```

### Option 3: Manual Installation

```bash
# Clone repository
git clone https://github.com/yourusername/ids-tool.git
cd ids-tool

# Create virtual environment (optional)
python3 -m venv myenv
source myenv/bin/activate  # On Windows: myenv\Scripts\activate

# Install dependencies
pip install -r requirements.txt

# Configure
python3 ids_cli.py setup

# Start server
python3 ids_cli.py start

# Access dashboard at http://localhost:5000
```

## CLI Commands

```bash
# Show welcome and help
ids-cli info

# Configure the IDS
ids-cli setup

# Start the server
ids-cli start

# Stop the server
ids-cli stop

# Check server status
ids-cli status

# View recent logs
ids-cli logs [-n 50]

# Show current configuration
ids-cli config

# Reset to default configuration
ids-cli reset

# Clear log file
ids-cli clear-logs
```

